Tom;<br>
But Rabshakeh said unto them, Hath my master sent me to thy master, and to thee, to speak these words? hath he not sent me to the men which sit on the wall, that they may eat their own dung, and drink their own piss with you? 2 Kings 18:27)<br><br>
Tom,<br>
I am not a fake, I speak my mind, always have. I don't lie to my congregation. That is why they are faithful to the Lord, not to me or to any particular denomination. They know the scriptures and how God feels about traitors and cowards. He much rather have individuals hot or cold bit not lukewarm, such individuals he pukes out of His mouth.  Compromising Christians that embrace all manner of false doctrines in order to appease the neighbor at the price of true Christianity he abhors. <br>
I believe when we stand before His presence we are going to be shocked at the words God will use to describe individuals that compromised His standards for the sake of a false peace.  <br>
That’s what happened to Christianity after the second century. Men put on robes and that made them holy in the eyes of the people but not before God. They received the praise of men because they served men and not God. <br>
Its easy to see how, God feels about Communistic countries and those who practice a passive and socialistic form of Christianity, which Christ strongly condemned in the New Testament.<br><br>
Tom weren't you the same that has been preaching to me over and over again about not judging others?<br>
I have from the onset judged and have not held back what is in my heart and what I see. I have been honest in all my postings. I don't live my life here any different then I do before God. <br><br>
Ask God what he will require of those that kept others from war because of their own weak hearts. Were they not destroyed by God’s righteous judgement? <br><br>
Tom, if you really must know, piss and dung is used throughout the Old and New Testament to figuratively express the idea of <br>
(a) worthlessness, especially a perishable article for which no one cares (&lt;1 Kin 14:10; 2 Kin 6:25; 9:37; Job 20:7; Ps 83:10; Jer 8:2; 9:22; 16:4; 25:33; Zeph 1:17; Phil 3:8&gt; (the American Standard Revised Version &quot;refuse&quot;). Dunghill was used in the same way &lt;1 Sam 2:8; Ezra 6:11; Ps 113:7; Isa 25:10; Dan 2:5; 3:29; Lk 14:35; Lam 4:5&gt;; <br>
(b) As an expression of disgust &lt;2 Kin 18:27; Isa 36:12&gt;; <br>
(c) of rebuke &lt;Mal 2:3&gt;.<br><br>
But God used those words to describe those He was irritated with, I wonder who will judge God for using those terms in describing the individuals he was angry with. <br>
I have an idea, Tom, why, don’t you ask him to give you an answer on why he speaks the way He does in His book. Of course you could always change the words as other churches are doing, because God’s ways or harsh words are no longer politically correct to use. Put on your robe Tom, if that's what makes you holy. <br>

